<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="25">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">Hypostomus ericius</taxonomicName>
can be separated from all other members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">H. cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group by coloration: light tan-gray with well-separated spots and no stripes. In addition, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">H. ericius</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
by a lack of a buccal papilla and from 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
by the presence of strong, sharp keels on the lateral plates. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">Hypostomus ericius</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
from which it differs mainly in coloration and morphometrics(Fig. 10B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="25">
Description: See 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7520B3CD-59C7-4425-A30E-1336A0B2AADD" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus cochliodon Kner 1854:265 [15]" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cochliodon">Hypostomus cochliodon</taxonomicName>
group description for more details. Morphometric data given in Table 1. Coloration generally tan-gray with large, widely-spaced spots. Spots present over entire body and becoming larger posteriorly. Caudal-fin membrane and rays often with black wash distally, and lighter area proximally instead of being spotted. Spots on fin spines and rays occasionally large. Spots less pronounced in juveniles, spots may be absent on abdomen. Juveniles with four faint dorsal saddles: first below anterior rays of dorsal fin, second below posterior rays of dorsal fin and slightly posterior to dorsal fin, third slightly anterior to and ventral to adipose fin, and fourth at base of caudal fin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="26" pageNumber="25">Dorsal fin moderately long, usually just barely reaching preadipose plate when depressed. Depressed pectoral-fin spine ventral to pelvic fin reaches beyond bases of pelvic-fin rays. Pectoral-fin spine supporting numerous stout, recurved, hypertrophied odontodes in nuptial males.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="28">
Keels sharp, very strongly developed. Orbits forming ridge distinctly raised above medial surface of head; ridges of dorsal and lateral aspect of head well-developed. Longitudinal ridge formed of raised bone and slightly larger odontodes absent on pterotic-supracleithrum beginning at postdorsal corner of orbit. Opercle usually not supporting odontodes, but sometimes up to 10 odontodes may be present on opercle (Fig. 2B). Nuptial body odontodes present (Fig. 2B). Plates in skin anterior to dorsal-fin spine usually absent or not numerous (Fig. 6A; Table 7). Cheek plates generally support several stout odontodes slightly larger than surrounding odontodes. Head appears wider and taller than in other species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E0BC8DAD-9CD9-4E32-920A-063D33AD0E80" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus Lacépède 1803:144" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hypostomus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="28">Each jaw with 5-9 teeth (mode = 7), teeth large and spoon-shaped. Average angle between dentaries 53° (SD = 9°; range: 40°-69°; N=7). Lateral line plates 27-28; dorsal plates 7-9; interdorsal plates 5-7; adipose caudal plates 9-10.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="28">
Range: Currently known from the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ríos">Rios</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Marañon">Maranon</normalizedToken>
, Itaya, and Nanay of the Upper 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Amazonas drainage of Peru (Fig. 11). 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C7C2629A-1686-4E4E-9E15-59B1D1162CBE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus ericius Armbruster 2003:25" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ericius">Hypostomus ericius</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4125CE0B-B466-47CA-B90F-CF9073FEE6F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypostomus hemicochliodon Armbruster 2003:29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hemicochliodon">H. hemicochliodon</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oculeus">H. oculeus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrineusi">H. pyrineusi</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="28">Etymology: From the Latin, ericius, for hedgehog in reference to the many sharp odontodes on the keels.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
